We have the goal $\int_0^x t \cdot \exp(t) \, dt = (x - 1) \cdot \exp(x) + 1$.

In Lean 4, we can prove this using the fundamental theorem of calculus (also known as the fundamental theorem of integral calculus). The fundamental theorem states that if we have an antiderivative of a function, we can compute the definite integral using the antiderivative.

From our manual calculation, the antiderivative of $t \cdot \exp(t)$ is $(t - 1) \cdot \exp(t)$.

So, $\int_0^x t \cdot \exp(t) \, dt = (x - 1) \cdot \exp(x) - (0 - 1) \cdot \exp(0)$.

Since $\exp(0) = 1$, we have: $(x - 1) \cdot \exp(x) - (0 - 1) \cdot 1 = (x - 1) \cdot \exp(x) + 1$.

